        <Relationship_Type>Parent/Child</Relationship_Type>
        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>cupboards (case furniture) [300039183], case furniture [300038860], storage and display furniture [300164528], furniture by form or function [300048628], furniture [300037680], furnishings by form or function [300037342], furnishings (works) [300037336], Furnishings (hierarchy name) [300037335], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Large but fairly low cupboards with an enclosed storage cabinet above and an open shelf or shelves below, or having two or three shelves and no enclosed cabinet. It is a type made in 16th- and 17th-century England and 17th-century America. Distinct from "press cupboards," which have both the upper and lower sections enclosed.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093897/Metropolitan Museum of Art [online] (2001-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Aparadores grandes, pero medianamente bajos con un gabinete de almacenamiento cerrado encima y una repisa o estantes abiertos debajo; de un tipo fabricado en el siglo XVI y XVII en Inglaterra y en el siglo XVII en América. Se diferencia de "press cupboard" que tiene ambas secciones, superior e inferior, cerradas.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Grote, maar tamelijk lage wandkasten met bovenin een opbergkast en onderin een openkast-systeem of planken. Dit type werd in de 16e en 17e eeuw in Engeland en in de 17e eeuw in Amerika gemaakt. Te onderscheiden van 'perskasten' die een dichte boven- en onderkant hebben.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>大型的矮櫥櫃，上有一封閉的儲藏櫃，下方則是開放式層架；此類櫥櫃製造於十六和十七世紀的英格蘭，以及十七世紀的美國。不同於「大櫃櫥」，後者的上下兩部分皆為封閉式空間。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
